1
00:00:04,144 --> 00:00:06,178
♪

2
00:00:16,389 --> 00:00:18,457
CARY: And does this abandoned pool

3
00:00:18,459 --> 00:00:20,025
belong to one of your
foreclosed properties?

4
00:00:20,027 --> 00:00:21,743
MAN: It belongs to one of the properties

5
00:00:21,745 --> 00:00:23,996
where the householder
could not repay his loan.

6
00:00:23,998 --> 00:00:26,415
And therefore, we exercised our prerogative

7
00:00:26,417 --> 00:00:29,001
as the bank holding the lease to foreclose.

8
00:00:29,003 --> 00:00:31,203
And this pool at 233 Graham Court...

9
00:00:31,205 --> 00:00:32,487
WOMAN: Can I interrupt here?

10
00:00:32,489 --> 00:00:35,207
It would save us all a lot
of time to just stipulate

11
00:00:35,209 --> 00:00:36,758
that the five swimming pools are part

12
00:00:36,760 --> 00:00:37,993
of the foreclosure package exercised

13
00:00:37,995 --> 00:00:39,294
by the Atlantic Commerce Bank.

14
00:00:39,296 --> 00:00:41,797
Good. If you stipulate to
that, it will save us time.

15
00:00:41,799 --> 00:00:43,832
I'll be right back.

16
00:00:43,834 --> 00:00:45,384
You okay, Kaley?

17
00:00:45,386 --> 00:00:47,269
Yeah. Thank you, Mr. Gardner.

18
00:00:47,271 --> 00:00:48,770
How's it going?

19
00:00:48,772 --> 00:00:50,171
Pulling teeth.

20
00:00:50,173 --> 00:00:51,339
What's that?

21
00:00:51,341 --> 00:00:52,724
Notice of mediation.

22
00:00:52,726 --> 00:00:53,725
For?

23
00:00:53,727 --> 00:00:55,727
Both of us. Wednesday.

24
00:00:55,729 --> 00:00:57,229
Why?

25
00:00:57,231 --> 00:00:58,780
The bankruptcy.

26
00:00:58,782 --> 00:01:00,399
We have another five weeks.

27
00:01:00,401 --> 00:01:02,517
- I know.
- We need 60 million by February.

28
00:01:02,519 --> 00:01:04,069
And yet, one of our creditors

29
00:01:04,071 --> 00:01:05,737
wants a mediation on our progress.

30
00:01:05,739 --> 00:01:07,355
- Which one?
- I don't know.

31
00:01:10,743 --> 00:01:12,027
Check with Clarke.

32
00:01:12,029 --> 00:01:14,613
If we're being called on
the carpet, he is, too.

33
00:01:14,615 --> 00:01:17,332
Hmm. Wouldn't hurt to
go in with the 15 million

34
00:01:17,334 --> 00:01:19,167
from Atlantic Commerce.

35
00:01:19,169 --> 00:01:21,202
We went down to 13.

36
00:01:21,204 --> 00:01:24,172
It would be nice to keep
that settlement above ten.

37
00:01:24,174 --> 00:01:25,974
I'm doing my best.

38
00:01:25,976 --> 00:01:27,559
Counsel, please tell your client
to stop evading and answer.

39
00:01:27,561 --> 00:01:28,727
WOMAN: Yes, after you rephrase.

40
00:01:28,729 --> 00:01:30,395
Very simply, sir, you
foreclosed on these...

41
00:01:30,397 --> 00:01:32,314
- The homeowners neglected to pay.
- You left these homes

42
00:01:32,316 --> 00:01:33,899
abandoned, you left these pools...

43
00:01:33,901 --> 00:01:36,101
- We did nothing. These pools?
- No, sir.

44
00:01:36,103 --> 00:01:37,236
After you kicked the homeowners out,

45
00:01:37,238 --> 00:01:38,520
you did nothing with the swimming pools.

46
00:01:38,522 --> 00:01:39,655
You let the water stagnate.

47
00:01:39,657 --> 00:01:41,523
- The water was stagnant already.
- And that water

48
00:01:41,525 --> 00:01:43,609
drew mosquitoes. These
mosquitoes, to be exact.

49
00:01:43,611 --> 00:01:46,061
And those mosquitoes carried
West Nile virus to my client,

50
00:01:46,063 --> 00:01:47,779
- Kaley Spence.
- WOMAN: Oh, come on.

51
00:01:47,781 --> 00:01:48,997
<i>Palsgraf v. Long Island Railroad.</i>

52
00:01:48,999 --> 00:01:50,398
There is no way that
Mr. Millam and his bank

53
00:01:50,400 --> 00:01:51,733
could know of this proximate cause.

54
00:01:51,735 --> 00:01:53,285
WILL: Good, then let your
client testify to that.

55
00:01:53,287 --> 00:01:56,455
Because what I have here
is a warning from the CDC

56
00:01:56,457 --> 00:01:57,706
mentioning your pools as the culprit.

57
00:01:57,708 --> 00:01:59,341
- We were not aware of that.
- "We"?

58
00:01:59,343 --> 00:02:00,876
Are we speaking for the whole bank here?

59
00:02:00,878 --> 00:02:02,794
- I was not aware of that.
- Well, were you aware

60
00:02:02,796 --> 00:02:04,129
of this letter of complaint written

61
00:02:04,131 --> 00:02:06,181
by the neighbors, including Mrs. Spence,

62
00:02:06,183 --> 00:02:09,417
about the declining conditions
of the foreclosed homes,

63
00:02:09,419 --> 00:02:10,769
including the pools?

64
00:02:10,771 --> 00:02:13,388
No. I was not aware of it. You can see

65
00:02:13,390 --> 00:02:14,806
- it was not addressed to me.
- Yes.

66
00:02:14,808 --> 00:02:17,059
It was addressed to your bank
president, Wilkes Ingersol.

67
00:02:17,061 --> 00:02:21,262
Luckily, that's who we're deposing next.

68
00:02:23,032 --> 00:02:27,286
♪ I love mountains, I love rolling hills ♪

69
00:02:27,288 --> 00:02:31,923
♪ I love the flowers,
I love the daffodils ♪

70
00:02:31,925 --> 00:02:36,028
♪ I love the fireside
when the lights are low ♪

71
00:02:36,030 --> 00:02:39,715
♪ Boom-dee-a-da, boom-dee-a-da,
boom-dee-a-da, boom... ♪

72
00:02:39,717 --> 00:02:41,466
<i>WILL: It's up to you now, Alicia.</i>

73
00:02:41,468 --> 00:02:44,136
<i>They sent it up the line
to the bank president.</i>

74
00:02:44,138 --> 00:02:45,721
I'm supposed to depose him in ten minutes.

75
00:02:45,723 --> 00:02:46,722
How's Minnesota?

76
00:02:46,724 --> 00:02:48,289
Quiet.

77
00:02:48,291 --> 00:02:50,892
WILL: Ask the president
if he ever saw the letter

78
00:02:50,894 --> 00:02:52,744
from the homeowners.
If he lies, we got them.

79
00:02:52,746 --> 00:02:53,845
They don't know we have the notes

80
00:02:53,847 --> 00:02:54,980
from the bank's quarterly meeting.

81
00:02:54,982 --> 00:02:56,932
Get his backtracking on record, and we win.

82
00:02:56,934 --> 00:02:59,067
Okay. I'll call you back in a few hours.

83
00:02:59,069 --> 00:03:00,468
♪ I love the ocean...

84
00:03:00,562 --> 00:03:02,579
Wow, look who's here.

85
00:03:02,581 --> 00:03:04,231
Everywhere I turn.

86
00:03:04,233 --> 00:03:07,334
Alicia. What a pleasant surprise.

87
00:03:07,336 --> 00:03:09,253
How's bankruptcy going?

88
00:03:09,255 --> 00:03:11,371
That which doesn't kill
us makes us stronger.

89
00:03:11,373 --> 00:03:13,573
Yeah, well, then you're
gonna be pretty strong.

90
00:03:13,575 --> 00:03:14,758
So, where are we?

91
00:03:14,760 --> 00:03:16,093
Uh, the business center.

92
00:03:16,095 --> 00:03:18,512
They got a business center here?

93
00:03:18,514 --> 00:03:21,665
For the record, I want
to restate our agreement.

94
00:03:21,667 --> 00:03:23,934
Mr. Ingersol's a busy man,
and he can only offer you

95
00:03:23,936 --> 00:03:25,552
three hours for your deposition.

96
00:03:25,554 --> 00:03:27,805
After that, he has to
get back to his ranch.

97
00:03:27,807 --> 00:03:28,856
For his vacation?

98
00:03:28,858 --> 00:03:29,740
His working vacation.

99
00:03:29,742 --> 00:03:31,525
Chopping wood? Milking cows?

100
00:03:31,527 --> 00:03:32,893
It's hard work.

101
00:03:32,895 --> 00:03:35,446
So, we're in agreement, Mrs.
Florrick, about three hours?

102
00:03:35,448 --> 00:03:37,231
If it's a true three hours, yes.

103
00:03:37,233 --> 00:03:39,149
And if you're in
agreement to have the judge

104
00:03:39,151 --> 00:03:41,068
on call so that she can immediately

105
00:03:41,070 --> 00:03:42,870
settle any and all objections.

106
00:03:42,872 --> 00:03:44,705
Yes, of course.

107
00:03:45,540 --> 00:03:47,541
Are you getting cell phone coverage here?

108
00:03:47,543 --> 00:03:51,712
If I stand on my bed and
put my arms over my head.

109
00:03:51,714 --> 00:03:53,747
Okay, we're ready.

110
00:03:54,615 --> 00:03:58,085
So, the clock will start as soon
as he walks through that door.

111
00:03:58,087 --> 00:03:59,803
As soon as he sits in that chair.

112
00:03:59,805 --> 00:04:01,555
Oh, let's not quibble.

113
00:04:01,557 --> 00:04:03,557
Good. Then the chair.

114
00:04:06,311 --> 00:04:08,345
<i>MAN: Wilkes Ingersol.</i>

115
00:04:08,347 --> 00:04:10,430
I'm the president of the
Atlantic Commerce Bank,

116
00:04:10,432 --> 00:04:12,266
and a trustee of the Mercantile Exchange.

117
00:04:12,268 --> 00:04:14,301
Well, it's nice to finally
meet you, Mr. Ingersol.

118
00:04:14,303 --> 00:04:15,769
You're a hard man to find.

119
00:04:15,771 --> 00:04:16,987
Really? Well...

120
00:04:16,989 --> 00:04:19,472
that's not what my accountant says.

121
00:04:19,474 --> 00:04:21,358
(laughter)

122
00:04:21,360 --> 00:04:24,077
We've been trying to depose
you for 14 months now.

123
00:04:24,079 --> 00:04:25,779
CANNING: Mrs. Florrick, if you wanted

124
00:04:25,781 --> 00:04:26,997
to read that into the record,

125
00:04:26,999 --> 00:04:28,499
you could have done so
before Mr. Ingersol arrived.

126
00:04:28,501 --> 00:04:30,784
INGERSOL: It's all right,
Louis. My apologies, ma'am.

127
00:04:30,786 --> 00:04:32,252
I don't mean to be flippant.

128
00:04:32,254 --> 00:04:34,454
Thank you for arranging this
deposition near my ranch.

129
00:04:34,456 --> 00:04:36,139
I hope you weren't inconvenienced.

130
00:04:36,141 --> 00:04:37,424
I'm fine.

131
00:04:37,426 --> 00:04:41,211
Now, sir, if we could turn
to these foreclosed homes

132
00:04:41,213 --> 00:04:42,963
and their swimming pools...

133
00:04:42,965 --> 00:04:46,016
- Yes. Um, could I say something first?
- Certainly, sir.

134
00:04:46,018 --> 00:04:47,935
I understand there are a lot of homeowners

135
00:04:47,937 --> 00:04:49,303
who are underwater.

136
00:04:49,305 --> 00:04:52,723
I understand many homebuyers
were enticed into taking on

137
00:04:52,725 --> 00:04:55,359
adjustable mortgages that
eventually bankrupt them.

138
00:04:55,361 --> 00:04:57,678
But what I often think is that banks

139
00:04:57,680 --> 00:04:59,863
are made the bad guys in these equations,

140
00:04:59,865 --> 00:05:01,514
and that is unwarranted.

141
00:05:01,516 --> 00:05:03,650
- Thank you, sir.
- But what I wholly condemn

142
00:05:03,652 --> 00:05:06,153
are any efforts to advance political causes

143
00:05:06,155 --> 00:05:07,404
through legal means.

144
00:05:07,406 --> 00:05:08,705
I mean, for example,

145
00:05:08,707 --> 00:05:10,457
uh, communities using eminent domain

146
00:05:10,459 --> 00:05:12,075
to address bank foreclosures.

147
00:05:12,077 --> 00:05:16,797
Or here, using this painful
circumstance of a young child

148
00:05:16,799 --> 00:05:20,100
with West Nile virus to force us to
change our methods on foreclosures.

149
00:05:20,102 --> 00:05:23,437
I think you've been
misinformed, Mr. Ingersol.

150
00:05:23,439 --> 00:05:26,506
Kaley Spence is suing you for $15 million.

151
00:05:26,508 --> 00:05:27,724
13 million.

152
00:05:27,726 --> 00:05:30,427
She's suing you because she had a
promising career as a ballet dancer,

153
00:05:30,429 --> 00:05:32,930
and now she needs full-time care.

154
00:05:32,932 --> 00:05:34,932
- We don't need the photos.
- I think we do.

155
00:05:34,934 --> 00:05:36,183
INGERSOL: Please leave them.

156
00:05:36,185 --> 00:05:38,151
She's a lovely girl.

157
00:05:38,153 --> 00:05:40,220
I have a 15-year-old daughter myself.

158
00:05:40,222 --> 00:05:41,438
ALICIA: Sir,

159
00:05:41,440 --> 00:05:43,657
did you see this letter,

160
00:05:43,659 --> 00:05:45,492
written by the residents
of the community complaining

161
00:05:45,494 --> 00:05:47,044
about the state of these foreclosed homes?

162
00:05:47,046 --> 00:05:48,278
CANNING: Objection. We have no foundation

163
00:05:48,280 --> 00:05:49,562
- for this letter. ALICIA:
- Mr. Canning, this is

164
00:05:49,564 --> 00:05:51,048
a deposition. There's
no need for foundation.

165
00:05:51,050 --> 00:05:52,866
That's not true, Mrs.
Florrick, and I won't have

166
00:05:52,868 --> 00:05:54,701
Mr. Ingersol sandbagged...

167
00:05:54,703 --> 00:05:56,036
Then let's call the judge.

168
00:05:56,038 --> 00:05:58,422
She made you sit down for this deposition.

169
00:05:58,424 --> 00:05:59,756
She will make you address my question.

170
00:05:59,758 --> 00:06:00,791
I'm sorry, Mrs. Florrick.

171
00:06:00,793 --> 00:06:01,925
We're gonna have to leave it there.

172
00:06:01,927 --> 00:06:03,510
No. Wha... wait a minute.

173
00:06:03,512 --> 00:06:06,964
INGERSOL: I just received an
emergency text I have to address.

174
00:06:06,966 --> 00:06:08,849
Sir, you have barely been
here for three minutes.

175
00:06:08,851 --> 00:06:10,350
I have only asked you one question.

176
00:06:10,352 --> 00:06:11,718
- Two.
- No, one.

177
00:06:11,720 --> 00:06:13,720
The judge was explicit in her ruling.

178
00:06:13,722 --> 00:06:15,105
If we made the effort
to be near your ranch,

179
00:06:15,107 --> 00:06:16,189
you must sit down with us

180
00:06:16,191 --> 00:06:17,524
- for at least three hours.
- And I will.

181
00:06:17,526 --> 00:06:19,943
- But, a in, this is an emergency.
- No, sir!

182
00:06:19,945 --> 00:06:22,145
I'll be back this afternoon at 2:00.

183
00:06:22,147 --> 00:06:23,363
Please be patient.

184
00:06:23,365 --> 00:06:24,564
You will get your time.

185
00:06:24,566 --> 00:06:25,932
I promise you.

186
00:06:28,036 --> 00:06:29,987
Well, that is unfortunate.

187
00:06:29,989 --> 00:06:32,605
<i>FRANK: No, I think you're doing well.</i>

188
00:06:32,607 --> 00:06:34,041
We expected a bump in Maddie's polling.

189
00:06:34,043 --> 00:06:35,626
She's the fresh new thing.

190
00:06:35,628 --> 00:06:36,793
Yes, we expected that, too.

191
00:06:36,795 --> 00:06:39,212
We're still beating her 47 to 42.5.

192
00:06:39,214 --> 00:06:40,447
That's outside the margin of error.

193
00:06:40,449 --> 00:06:42,499
I know. We're not worried.

194
00:06:42,501 --> 00:06:45,052
And yet you're here.

195
00:06:45,887 --> 00:06:47,421
It's a visit.

196
00:06:47,423 --> 00:06:48,639
The Democratic Committee

197
00:06:48,641 --> 00:06:50,557
has a lot invested in your boy Florrick.

198
00:06:50,559 --> 00:06:52,342
We want to make sure he wins.

199
00:06:52,344 --> 00:06:53,677
And you're worried he won't?

200
00:06:53,679 --> 00:06:55,929
I'm worried the sun
won't rise tomorrow, Eli.

201
00:06:55,931 --> 00:06:57,314
It's a visit. That's all.

202
00:06:57,316 --> 00:06:58,965
Thank you.

203
00:06:58,967 --> 00:07:00,851
Come again sometime.

204
00:07:00,853 --> 00:07:03,837
I heard something.

205
00:07:05,206 --> 00:07:07,741
Something that worried me.

206
00:07:07,743 --> 00:07:09,743
I heard your offices were raided.

207
00:07:09,745 --> 00:07:11,078
It's nothing, Frank.

208
00:07:11,080 --> 00:07:12,162
It's not nothing.

209
00:07:12,164 --> 00:07:14,748
<i>No raid is nothing. A raid is something.</i>

210
00:07:14,750 --> 00:07:15,866
- It's not about the candidate.
- I know it's not

211
00:07:15,868 --> 00:07:17,617
about the candidate. It's about you.

212
00:07:19,270 --> 00:07:22,005
(closing door): I'm not
hiding anything from you.

213
00:07:22,007 --> 00:07:25,592
There are forces within
the Justice Department

214
00:07:25,594 --> 00:07:27,594
that do not want Peter
to win the governorship.

215
00:07:27,596 --> 00:07:29,680
Now, they don't have the
facts to come after him,

216
00:07:29,682 --> 00:07:32,182
so they're coming after me
as a steppingstone to Peter.

217
00:07:32,184 --> 00:07:34,851
- And they have the facts to come after you?
- N... no.

218
00:07:34,853 --> 00:07:37,504
I'm just saying, they know

219
00:07:37,506 --> 00:07:39,672
that Peter without me would be limping.

220
00:07:39,674 --> 00:07:41,475
So, they want this.

221
00:07:41,477 --> 00:07:44,728
They want you coming to me suggesting...

222
00:07:46,030 --> 00:07:47,814
What are you suggesting?

223
00:07:49,016 --> 00:07:50,617
Not that you resign.

224
00:07:50,619 --> 00:07:51,902
You're not an issue yet.

225
00:07:51,904 --> 00:07:53,453
But you need a strong second

226
00:07:53,455 --> 00:07:55,238
in case you do become an issue.

227
00:07:55,240 --> 00:07:57,624
- I know you don't like it, Eli.
- (laughs quietly)

228
00:07:57,626 --> 00:07:59,209
But you need a second.

229
00:07:59,211 --> 00:08:01,495
♪

230
00:08:12,056 --> 00:08:13,490
So, 2:00 p.m., huh?

231
00:08:13,492 --> 00:08:15,892
Yes. I'm not sure what happened.

232
00:08:15,894 --> 00:08:17,811
The judge won't be happy.

233
00:08:17,813 --> 00:08:19,846
Mr. Ingersol is a very...

234
00:08:19,848 --> 00:08:22,682
If I hear one more time
how busy Mr. Ingersol is,

235
00:08:22,684 --> 00:08:24,050
I will strangle you.

236
00:08:24,052 --> 00:08:26,236
(phone rings)

237
00:08:27,071 --> 00:08:28,488
Hello?

238
00:08:28,490 --> 00:08:31,491
Yeah, yeah. I understand.

239
00:08:31,493 --> 00:08:34,244
No, uh, she's here. I'll tell her.

240
00:08:34,246 --> 00:08:35,996
Okay, thank you. Bye.

241
00:08:35,998 --> 00:08:37,781
Mr. Ingersol would like to apologize...

242
00:08:37,783 --> 00:08:40,283
- Let's get the judge on the line.
- It's an emergency.

243
00:08:40,285 --> 00:08:42,536
He said he just has to
delay until tomorrow morning.

244
00:08:42,538 --> 00:08:43,954
He set aside three hours starting at 10:00.

245
00:08:43,956 --> 00:08:45,589
He won't count today's
ten minutes against it.

246
00:08:45,591 --> 00:08:47,591
He wanted me to apologize
to you personally.

247
00:08:47,593 --> 00:08:50,260
He said he really enjoyed his
time with you this morning.

248
00:08:50,262 --> 00:08:54,431
Let the record reflect that Mr.
Ingersol has refused to attend...

249
00:08:54,433 --> 00:08:56,299
- He didn't refuse to attend.
- ... failed to appear

250
00:08:56,301 --> 00:08:59,803
in a court-mandated deposition,
despite promising to attend

251
00:08:59,805 --> 00:09:02,773
between the hours of
2:00 and 5:00 p.m. today.

252
00:09:02,775 --> 00:09:04,591
Alicia, you might want
to look at this tonight.

253
00:09:04,593 --> 00:09:06,059
The CDC has revised their report.

254
00:09:06,061 --> 00:09:08,262
It seems there's another
